_rawBody:
Nadira owns a clothes shop.

\begin{parts}
\item The pictogram shows the number of skirts that were sold each day in one week.

\begin{InsertScreenShot}
    \relincludegraphics{Figures/Q01-Pictogram.png}
\end{InsertScreenShot}

\begin{subparts}
\item On which day were most skirts sold?
\AnswerLine[][]
\Marks{1}

\item How many skirts were sold on Wednesday?
\AnswerLine[][]
\Marks{1}

\item Work out how many more skirts were sold on Friday than on Thursday.
\AnswerLine[][]
\Marks{1}
\end{subparts}

\item The shop is open for 6 days each week.\\
On each day, the shop is open from 09 30 until 13 00 and from 14 15 until 20 30.\\
Work out the total number of hours the shop is open in one week.
\AnswerLine[][hours]
\Marks{2}

\item Nadira pays 6 people to work in the shop.\\
In one week
\begin{parts}
    \item 4 people each work for 38 hours
    \item 2 people each work for 25 hours.
\end{parts}
They are each paid \$11.40 for each hour they work.\\
Calculate the total amount Nadira pays these 6 people in one week.
\AnswerLine[\$][]
\Marks{2}

\item Nadira has some T-shirts that are either white or blue or green.\\
The numbers of T-shirts are in the ratio white : blue : green = 5 : 4 : 1.\\
48 of the T-shirts are blue.\\
Work out the total number of T-shirts.
\AnswerLine[][]
\Marks{3}

\item Nadira buys a pack of 40 dresses and pays \$500.\\
She sells 35 of these dresses for \$22 each.\\
She sells the remaining 5 dresses for \$14.50 each.\\
Calculate the percentage profit she makes when she sells all 40 dresses.
\AnswerLine[][\%]
\Marks{4}

\end{parts}

